- ## Forms
#Forms  #Models #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
There are two basic forms: the program form and the sequence form.

- ## Program
#Program #Form #Forms  #Models #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
Program Form. A GOMS model in program form is analogous to a parameterized computer program. The methods take any admissible set of task parameters and will execute the corresponding instance of the task correctly

- ## Program
#Program #Form #Forms  #Models #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
a program form model is a compact, generative3 description that explicitly represents the knowledge of what features of the task environment the user should attend to and how the user should operate the system to accomplish the task goals.

- ## Program
#Program #Form #Forms  #Models #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
advantage that all procedural knowledge is visible to the analyst.

- ## Sequence
#Sequence #Form #Forms  #Models #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
Sequence Form. In contrast, the methods in a sequence-form GOMS model contain a fixed sequence of operators for accomplishing a particular task instance

- ## Sequence
#Sequence #Form #Forms  #Models #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
may be some conditionality and parameters included in the sequence model.

- ## Sequence
#Sequence #Form #Forms  #Models #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
advantages and disadvantages of the sequence form are the inverse of the program form. That is, the analyst does not have to explicitly define the procedural knowledge for every possible task situation in program-like detail, and the sequence of operators is clearly visible to the analyst.

- ## Sequence
#Sequence #Form #Forms  #Models #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
if a large number of task instances are involved, it could be time consuming to construct and evaluate the corresponding large number of sequence form models.

- ## Characteristics
#Characteristics #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
GOMS model can, and should, start at a high level of a task such as collaboratively writing a research paper with a coauthor. At such a high level, the subtasks involve many different applications

- ## Characteristics
#Characteristics #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
The assumed cognitive architectures range from the trivial, in the case of the KLM, to slightly more complicated for CMN-GOMS, to an elaborated sequential architecture with a working memory and specified procedure knowledge representation in NGOMSL, to a powerful but relatively unspec- ified multiple parallel processor architecture in CPM-GOMS

- ## Characteristics

By using descriptions of user procedures, the techniques can provide quantitative predictions of procedure learning and execution time and qualitative in- sights into the implications of design features

- ## Goals
#Goals #Components #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
Goals are what the user has to accomplish. The common- sense meaning of the term applies here; a goal is the “end towards which effort is directed

- ## Goals
#Goals #Components #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
Goals are often broken down into subgoals; all of the subgoals must be accomplished in order to achieve the overall goal

- ## Goals
#Goals #Components #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
Goals versus Operators: Level of Detail. It is important to clarify a common point of confusion about goals and operators. The distinction is strictly one of the required level of detail:

- ## Operators
#Operators #Components #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
An operator is an action performed in service of a goal. Operators can be perceptual, cognitive, or motor acts, or a compos- ite of these

- ## Operators
#Operators #Components #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
The important parameters of operators, in particular execution time, are assumed to be independent of how the user or the system got into the current state

- ## Methods
#Methods #Components #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
Methods are sequences of operators and subgoal invoca- tions that accomplish a goal. If the goals have a hierarchical form, then there is a corresponding hierarchy of methods.

- ## Selection
#Selection #Rules #Components #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
If there is more than one method applicable to a goal, then selection rules are necessary to represent the user’s knowledge of which method should be applied. Typically such rules are based on specific properties of the task instance

- ## CMNGOMS
#CMNGOMS #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
original formulation of GOMS, which we will refer to as CMN-GOMS;

- ## CMNGOMS
#CMNGOMS #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
CMN-GOMS is the term we use to refer to the form of GOMS model presented in Card et al. [1983, Ch. 5] and Card et al. [1980b]. CMN-GOMS has a strict goal hierarchy

- ## CMNGOMS
#CMNGOMS #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
Methods are represented in an informal program form that can include submethods and conditionals. A CMN- GOMS model, given a particular task situation, can thus predict both operator sequence and execution time.

- ## CMNGOMS
#CMNGOMS #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
CMN-GOMS is based on two of the MHP “Principles of Opera- tion,” the Rationality Principle and the Problem Space Principle, both of which developed in the problem-solving theoretical literature (e.g., Newell and Simon [1972] and Card et al. [1983, Ch. 11])

- ## CMNGOMS
#CMNGOMS #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
major difference between the KLM and the CMN-GOMS models is that CMN-GOMS is in program form; therefore, the analysis is general and executable

- ## CMNGOMS
#CMNGOMS #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
CMN-GOMS, once its program methods have been worked out, can predict execution time for all subsumed task instances

- ## CPMGOMS
#CPMGOMS #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
Cognitive-Perceptual-Motor GOMS (CPM-GOMS) CPM-GOMS, like the other GOMS models, predicts execution time based on an analysis of component activities.

- ## CPMGOMS
#CPMGOMS #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
CPM-GOMS requires a specific level of analysis where the primitive operators are simple percep- tual, cognitive, and motor acts. Unlike the other extant GOMS techniques, CPM-GOMS does not make the assumption that operators are performed serially

- ## CPMGOMS
#CPMGOMS #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling

- ## CPMGOMS
#CPMGOMS #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
CPM-GOMS technique directly applies the MHP to a task analysis by identifying the operators that must be performed by each processor and the sequential dependencies between them.

- ## CPMGOMS
#CPMGOMS #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
allows parallelism between CPM-GOMS opera- tors, which is necessary for analyzing some tasks, but it also forces the primitive operators to be at the level of the cycle-times of the MHP’s processors

- ## CPMGOMS
#CPMGOMS #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling

- ## KLM
#KLM #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
the simplest version presented by Card, Moran, and Newell, called the Keystroke-Level Model (KLM)

- ## KLM
#KLM #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
Keystroke-Level Model (KLM) is the simplest GOMS technique [Card et al. 1980a; 1983, Ch. 8]. To estimate execution time for a task, the analyst lists the sequence of operators and then totals the execution times for the individual operators.

- ## KLM
#KLM #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
original KLM presentation included six types of operators: K to press a key or button, P to point with a mouse to a target on a display, H to home hands on the keyboard or other device, D to draw a line segment on a grid, M to mentally prepare to do an action or a closely related series of primitive actions, and R to represent the system response time during which the user has to wait for the system

- ## KLM
#KLM #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
KLM technique includes a set of five heuristic rules for placing mental operators to account for mental preparation time during a task that requires several physical operators

- ## KLM
#KLM #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
KLM is based on a simple underlying cognitive architecture: a serial stage model of human information processing in which one activity is done at a time until the task is complete. All of the human information-processing activity is assumed to be contained in the primitive operators,

- ## KLM
#KLM #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
KLM is easy to apply, but predicts only execution time, and only from analyst-supplied methods.

- ## NGOMSL
#NGOMSL #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
more rigorous version called NGOMSL

- ## NGOMSL
#NGOMSL #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
Natural GOMS Language (NGOMSL) NGOMSL is a structured natural-language notation for representing GOMS models and a procedure for constructing them [Kieras 1988; 1996].

- ## NGOMSL
#NGOMSL #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
NGOMSL model is in program form and provides predictions of operator sequence, execution time, and time to learn the methods. An analyst constructs an NGOMSL model by performing a top-down, breadth-first expansion

- ## NGOMSL
#NGOMSL #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
NGOMSL technique refines the basic GOMS concept by representing methods in terms of a cognitive architecture called cognitive complexity theory

- ## NGOMSL
#NGOMSL #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
CCT prediction results can be used by NGOMSL models to estimate not only execution time like KLM and CMN-GOMS, but also the time to learn the procedures

- ## NGOMSL
#NGOMSL #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
Because NGOMSL models specify methods in program form, they can characterize the procedural complexity of tasks, both in terms of how much must be learned and how much has to be executed. However, the underly- ing simple serial-stage architecture of CCT limits NGOMSL to hierarchical and sequential methods

- ## NGOMSL
#NGOMSL #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
Quantitatively, NGOMSL provides learning time as well as execution time predictions, discussed in detail below. Qualitatively, NGOMSL pro- vides all that KLM and CMN-GOMS provide, and more. For example, NGOMSL makes the similarity between methods explicit

- ## NGOMSL
#NGOMSL #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
Transfer of training effects can be calculated by deducting the number of NGOMSL statements in methods that are identical, or highly similar, to ones already known to the learner (see Kieras [1988; 1996] and Bovair et al. [1988; 1990]). This characterization of interface consistency in terms of the quantitative transferability of proce- dural knowledge is perhaps the most significant contribution of the CCT research and the NGOMSL technique

- ## NGOMSL
#NGOMSL #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
The primary difference between execution time predictions for NGOMSL, KLM, and CMN-GOMS is how time is assigned to cognitive and perceptual operators.

- ## NGOMSL
#NGOMSL #GOMS #Task #Models #Task #Modelling #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
NGOMSL, with the additional invest- ment in its explicit representation of procedural knowledge, can then also predict some aspects of learning time

- ## Model
#Model #Human #Processor #Human #Information #Processing #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
Problem Space Principle postulates that a user’s activity can be characterized as applying a sequence of actions, called operators, to transform an initial state into a goal state.

- ## Model
#Model #Human #Processor #Human #Information #Processing #Task #Analysis  #Modeling 
Rationality Principle asserts that users will develop methods that are efficient, given the structure of the task environ- ment (i.e., the design of the system) and human processing abilities and limitations. Thus, human activity with a computer system can be viewed as executing methods to accomplish goals
